Higher education continues to face challenges in meeting students' accessibility needs for course content, including assignment instructions and reference materials. Furthermore, the complexity of accessibility concepts raises significant barriers to making necessary improvements. This work introduces Iris, a course content management system that focuses on presentation, interactivity, and accessibility improvements, with minimal effort required from authors. Iris provides accessibility, usability, and customization features, including font and spacing settings, reading rulers, and heading-based navigation, to readers throughout the platform. Additionally, using a large language model (LLM), Iris provides language-based accommodation through three strategies: hinting, simplifying, and explaining. This feature uses a simple one-click interface to uphold interactions with course staff. In line with universal design (UD) principles, Iris's features are designed for all students, but especially target students with disabilities and, for the LLM-based features, nonnative English speakers and students unfamiliar with the topic. Iris uses a custom document format and editor to enable its various features, prevent semantic HTML errors, and leave flexibility for future enhancements. Iris can distribute text-based content for any course, but was initially evaluated in introductory computer science courses. We deployed the platform to display assignment instructions and conducted surveys in three quarters to evaluate students' experience. The most recent survey, conducted in Fall 2025, compares Iris with the previous system used in the course. The results reveal a significant preference for Iris. However, students with disabilities were underrepresented in the sample. In the future, we plan to conduct targeted research to address this issue.